post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_11143109_11143184_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.7857142857142857, "section_id": 3759}}, "n3337": {"so_11143109_11143184_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.7857142857142857, "section_id": 3621}}, "n4659": {"so_11143109_11143184_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 0.5714285714285714, "section_id": 4526}}}, "11143109": {"ViewCount": "712", "Body": "<p>Does <code>valarray</code> have contiguous memory alignment?  </p>\n<p>I want to pass a valarray to a function (from IPPS), which only takes pointers, by passing <code>&amp;myValarray[0]</code>. But therefore I should be sure, that valarray's memory alignment is contiguous.</p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>\n", "Title": "Does valarray have contiguous memory alignment?", "CreationDate": "2012-06-21T16:59:46.350", "LastActivityDate": "2012-06-22T06:51:55.123", "CommentCount": "4", "LastEditDate": "2012-06-22T06:51:55.123", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "1465908", "Id": "11143109", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "1465908", "Tags": "<c++><arrays><stl><memory-alignment>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "11143184": {"Id": "11143184", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Assuming you're asking whether the memory managed by a valarray is guaranteed to be <em>contiguous</em>, then the answer is yes, at least if the object isn't <code>const</code> (C++03, \u00a726.3.2.3/3 or C++11, \u00a726.6.2.4/2):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_11143109_11143184_0\">The expression &amp;a[i+j] == &amp;a[i] + j evaluates as true for all size_t i and size_t j such\n  that i+j is less than the length of the non-constant array a.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-06-21T17:05:35.410", "CommentCount": "2", "CreationDate": "2012-06-21T17:05:35.410", "ParentId": "11143109", "Score": "10", "OwnerUserId": "179910"}});